Integrate protein expression datasets, divided by Batch and Donor

Raymond Louie

03 September, 2022

1 Load libraries and read seurat objects

library(Matrix)
library(dplyr)
library(Seurat)
library(ggplot2)
library(grid)
require(gridExtra)
library(data.table)
library(knitr)
library(kableExtra)

seurat_gene = readRDS("../adaptive_gene.rds")
seurat_protein = readRDS("../10_1016_j_cell_2021_02_018_adaptive_protein.rds")

The following steps mimic those in https://satijalab.org/seurat/articles/integration_introduction.html. For more information, please see this link

2 Normalize each batch-donor dataset

Normalize each batch_donor data. Note that the original paper Time-resolved systems immunology reveals a late juncture linked to fatal COVID-19, Cell 2021 performed clustering on the gene expression data by regressing out Batch and Donor information. We thus assume these two factors contribute to unwanted technical effects to the data, and thus Seurats integration pipeline will be used to correct for these technical differences.

meta_df = seurat_protein@meta.data
meta_df$batch_donor = paste0(meta_df$Batch,"_",
                             meta_df$Donor)
unique_batch_donor = unique(meta_df$batch_donor)
# unique_batch_donor=unique_batch_donor[1:2]

seurat_protein.list = list()
for (ind in 1:length(unique_batch_donor)){
  curr_batch_donor = unique_batch_donor[[ind]]
  keep_cells = rownames(meta_df)[which(meta_df$batch_donor %in% curr_batch_donor)]
  curr_matrix = seurat_protein@assays$ADT@data[,keep_cells]
  curr_meta_gene = seurat_gene@meta.data[keep_cells,]
  curr_meta_protein = seurat_protein@meta.data[keep_cells,]
  curr_meta = cbind(curr_meta_gene,
                    curr_meta_protein[,setdiff(colnames(curr_meta_protein),
                                               colnames(curr_meta_gene))])
  
  curr_seurat <- CreateSeuratObject(counts = curr_matrix,
                                    meta.data =curr_meta)
  curr_seurat <- NormalizeData(curr_seurat, normalization.method = "CLR", margin = 2)
  seurat_protein.list[[curr_batch_donor]] = curr_seurat    
}

3 Integration

immune.anchors <- FindIntegrationAnchors(object.list = seurat_protein.list, anchor.features = rownames(seurat_protein))
# this command creates an 'integrated' data assay
immune.combined <- IntegrateData(anchorset = immune.anchors)

4 Integrated analysis and visualization

# specify that we will perform downstream analysis on the corrected data note that the
# original unmodified data still resides in the 'RNA' assay
DefaultAssay(immune.combined) <- "integrated"

# Run the standard workflow for visualization and clustering
immune.combined <- ScaleData(immune.combined, verbose = FALSE)
immune.combined <- RunPCA(immune.combined, npcs = 30, verbose = FALSE)
immune.combined <- RunUMAP(immune.combined, reduction = "pca", dims = 1:30)
Idents(immune.combined) = immune.combined$cell_type

# Visualization
p1 <- DimPlot(immune.combined, reduction = "umap", group.by = "Batch")
p2 <- DimPlot(immune.combined, reduction = "umap", label = TRUE, repel = TRUE)
p1 + p2

5 Save integrated seurat object

integrated_seurat_protein = immune.combined
saveRDS(integrated_seurat_protein,
        file="integrated_seurat_protein.rds")
